Detecting Plant Diseases with PyTorch
A Pipeline for Real-Time Crop Health Monitoring
Abstract:
This tutorial showcases a machine learning pipeline using PyTorch with the objective of detecting plant diseases from crop leaf images presenting symptoms like discolouration, spots, and wilting. The PlantVillage dataset is chosen for this purpose, and the pipeline includes data preprocessing with augmentation, splitting the dataset, and the development of a custom convolutional neural network (CNN). Hyperparameter experiments are also conducted to evaluate the impact of different learning rates, dropout levels, and batch sizes, with results visualised through graphs and tables to evaluate the different variations.

1. Introduction

Welcome to this tutorial where we explore the application of Artificial Intelligence (AI) in the context of agricultural practices. As the global population increases, agriculture needs innovative solutions to help manage crop diseases. This tutorial uses PyTorch to develop a machine learning pipeline that detects plant diseases early, with the goal of reducing crop losses and minimising pesticide use, hopefully improving agricultural practices.

1.1 Motivation: AI for Sustainable Agriculture

The integration of AI into agriculture can lead to earlier detection of plant diseases. Early detection of plant diseases can significantly reduce crop losses and minimise the need for pesticides, leading to healthier and more sustainable farming practices. This tutorial demonstrates how deep learning, specifically using PyTorch, can be applied to real-world agricultural challenges. This has the potential to help farmers by increasing the overall yield of crops. The importance of this can also be seen through the various health and environmental issues caused by pesticides which will be used less due to this model.

2. Data Management

This chapter walks through the selection and use of the PlantVillage dataset in the application of AI for agricultural challenges, specifically in identifying plant diseases. We'll explore the dataset's composition, its classes, and the potential challenges it presents for AI-driven disease detection.

2.1 Overview of the PlantVillage Dataset

The PlantVillage dataset is a large collection of images containing both healthy and diseased crop leaves across multiple plant species. It is used in this tutorial as the dataset for developing a machine learning model that can accurately recognise various plant diseases.

Structure:

  • Classes: Organised into 38 distinct categories, each class corresponds to a specific plant condition, either healthy or diseased, and is stored in separate folders.

Accessibility:

  • The dataset is freely accessible on Kaggle, with freedom for anyone to use. You can download it directly here.

Challenges:

  • Variability in Image Quality: The images vary in resolution and lighting conditions, which makes developing a robust AI model more difficult, but also more realistic.
  • Visual Similarity: The resemblance between symptoms of different plant diseases makes developing a highly accurate model more difficulty meaning more careful modelling techniques should be used.

# Define the directory where the PlantVillage dataset is stored

# Define transformations for the dataset
transform = transforms.Compose([
    transforms.Resize(256),                           # Resize the shorter side of the image to 256
    transforms.CenterCrop(224),                       # Crop the central 224x224 region
    transforms.RandomHorizontalFlip(),                # Augmentation
    transforms.RandomRotation(30),                    # Augmentation
    transforms.ToTensor(),                            # Convert images to PyTorch tensors
    transforms.Normalize(mean=[0.485, 0.456, 0.406],  # ImageNet means
                         std=[0.229, 0.224, 0.225])   # ImageNet stds
])

Tip: PyTorchs ImageFolder is used for its efficiency in handling large image datasets. It automatically associates images with labels based on the directory structure. This simplifies the management of large-scale datasets and also accurately assigns labels.

Note: Each transformation applied serves a specific purpose:

  • Resizing and Cropping help reduce the computational load and ensure that the images are of a uniform size, which is essential for batch processing.
  • Normalisation aligns the data distribution with the pre-trained models on ImageNet, improving model training efficiency and aiding in faster convergence. The values used for mean and standard deviation ([0.485, 0.456, 0.406] and [0.229, 0.224, 0.225], respectively) are commonly used, derived from the ImageNet dataset to standardise images in a similar way to how models were originally trained. This approach can be found in videos like "Understanding PyTorch with a Comprehensive Tutorial" by CodeWithAarohi.

def show_images(images, labels, num_rows=2, num_cols=2, title=None):
    """Display a grid of images with labels, showing label names instead of numbers."""
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(num_rows, num_cols, figsize=(12, 8))  
    axes = axes.flatten()
    for i, (img, ax) in enumerate(zip(images, axes)):
        img = img.numpy().transpose((1, 2, 0))
        mean = np.array([0.485, 0.456, 0.406])  # Normalising mean
        std = np.array([0.229, 0.224, 0.225])   # Normalising standard deviation
        img = std * img + mean                  # Unnormalise the image
        img = np.clip(img, 0, 1)                # Making sure the image values are valid
        ax.imshow(img)
        ax.set_title(f'Label: {color_dataset.classes[labels[i]]}', fontsize=10, y=-0.15)  # Adjust label position
        ax.axis('off')
    plt.tight_layout()
    if title:
        plt.subplots_adjust(top=0.85)  
        plt.suptitle(title, fontsize=16, y=0.95)  
    plt.show()
    
def plot_label_distribution(labels, classes):
    """Plot a bar chart showing label distribution."""
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6)) 
    counts = np.bincount(labels)
    plt.bar(classes, counts, color='skyblue')
    plt.xlabel('Labels')
    plt.ylabel('Count')
    plt.title('Label Distribution in Dataset')
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)  
    plt.show()

2.4 Splitting Data into Train/Validation/Test Sets

Proper data management is essential for effective machine learning. We need to divide the data into separate sets for training, validation, and testing. This segmentation facilitates the different phases of model training and ensures a systematic approach to model evaluation:

  • Training Set (70% of the dataset): The majority of the data is used for training the model. This set helps the model learn the characteristics of various plant diseases and healthy plant conditions from the augmented images, aiming to improve its ability to make accurate predictions.

  • Validation Set (15% of the dataset): The validation subset tunes the model's parameters and prevents overfitting. Regular validation during the training process allows for ongoing adjustments and improvements to the model's architecture and learning parameters based on performance metrics that the validation data provides.

  • Test Set (15% of the dataset): After training, this set is used to evaluate the model's final performance. It provides an unbiased assessment of how well the model can generalise new, unseen data, which is needed to evaluate the model by seeing how it will practically work in real-world scenarios.

3. Custom CNN Architecture for Plant Disease Detection

This chapter explores the construction and functionality of a custom Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) specifically designed for the task of detecting plant diseases from images.

3.1 Custom CNN: Layer-by-Layer Implementation

The custom CNN below, PlantDiseaseCNN, includes two main convolutional blocks followed by pooling, dropout for regularisation, and fully-connected layers to perform classification. The development of this model was informed by best practices and examples from the PyTorch documentation, as well as practical insights from the YouTube tutorial "Exploring Machine Learning with PyTorch" by Nicholas Renotte, which discusses machine learning techniques using PyTorch.

In[6]:
class PlantDiseaseCNN(nn.Module):
    """
    Custom CNN for plant disease classification. This model includes convolutional layers, 
    max pooling, dropout for regularisation, and fully-connected layers.
    """
    def __init__(self, num_classes, dropout_prob=0.5):
        super(PlantDiseaseCNN, self).__init__()
        
        # Feature extractor
        self.features = nn.Sequential(
            # First convolutional layer processes 3-channel images (RGB), using 32 filters of size 3x3.
            nn.Conv2d(3, 32, kernel_size=3, padding=1),  # Input: 3-channel 224x224
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2),  # Output: 32x112x112
            nn.Conv2d(32, 64, kernel_size=3, padding=1),  # Input: 32x112x112
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2),  # Output: 64x56x56
            nn.Dropout(dropout_prob)      # Regularization layer to prevent overfitting
        )
        # Classifier
        self.classifier = nn.Sequential(
            # Flatten the output of the feature extractor to pass to the fully connected layer.
            nn.Linear(64*56*56, 128),  # Flatten: 64*56*56
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Dropout(dropout_prob),
            nn.Linear(128, num_classes)
        )

    # Forward pass through the network
    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.features(x)
        x = x.view(x.size(0), -1)  # Flatten the output for the classifier
        return self.classifier(x)  # Pass the flattened output through the classifier

# Initialise the model
num_classes = len(color_dataset.classes)
model = PlantDiseaseCNN(num_classes=num_classes, dropout_prob=0.5)
print(f"Model has been initalised with {num_classes} output classes")

Model has been initalised with 38 output classes

Detailed Explanation of the PlantDiseaseCNN Architecture

After setting up the PlantDiseaseCNN class, it is important to understand each component and its role in the model. This understanding will aid in grasping how the model processes input images and makes classifications:

Convolutional Layers

  • First Convolutional Block:

    • Layer Input: Takes an input with 3 colour channels (RGB) and a resolution of 224x224 pixels.
    • Convolution (Conv2d): Applies 32 filters of size 3x3 with padding set to 1. This layer helps in detecting basic features like edges and textures without reducing the spatial dimensions due to padding.
    • Activation (ReLU): Applies the Rectified Linear Unit activation function which brings non-linearity to the model, allowing it to learn more complex patterns.
    • Pooling (MaxPool2d): Applies a 2x2 max pooling operation which reduces the spatial dimensions of the output from the previous layer by half (from 224x224 to 112x112). This reduces the computational complexity and helps in making the detection of features invariant to scale and orientation.

  • Second Convolutional Block:

    • Layer Input: Receives the output from the first block, now with 32 feature maps of size 112x112.
    • Convolution (Conv2d): Increases the depth of the feature maps from 32 to 64 using filters of the same size (3x3) with padding, maintaining the dimension due to padding.
    • Activation (ReLU): Continues to add non-linearity to the model, useful for learning deeper features required for the plant images.
    • Pooling (MaxPool2d): Further reduces the dimensions from 112x112 to 56x56, focusing the model on the most prominent and salient features.

Regularisation (Dropout)

  • Dropout: After each pooling operation, dropout is applied with a probability of 0.5. This randomly zeroes some of the feature maps, which helps prevent overfitting by ensuring that no single set of neurons has too much responsibility for accurate predictions.

Fully Connected Layers (Classifier)

  • Flattening: Before passing into fully connected layers, the output from the last pooling layer is flattened into a single long vector.
  • First Linear Layer (Linear): Transforms the flattened vector from the convolutional base into a vector of size 128. This layer begins the process of classification, interpreting the features extracted by the convolutions.
  • Activation (ReLU): Adds non-linearity after the first fully connected layer.
  • Second Linear Layer (Linear): Reduces the dimension from 128 to the number of classes (num_classes), which corresponds to the number of plant diseases the model is trained to identify.

In this section, we prepare the computational environment and settings needed for training our neural network. The optimiser is also defined here, which is crucial for updating network weights effectively during training.

Using a GPU can significantly accelerate the training due to it being able to perform parallel operations, which is crucial for handling the computationally intensive tasks involved in training deep neural networks. This optimisation ensures your model can run efficiently on the most appropriate hardware at your disposal.

4.2 Training and Validation Loops

Training and validating the neural network involves multiple cycles (epochs) where the model learns from the training data and then checks its understanding by predicting on a separate validation set. This process helps us fine-tune the model parameters without seeing the test data, ensuring that we gauge the model's performance under unbiased conditions. The principles discussed in this section were developed with knowledge learnt through a course, which can be viewed here by freeCodeCamp.org.

In[9]:
# Define the train_model function to manage both training and validation phases
def train_model(model, train_loader, val_loader, optimizer, num_epochs=10):
    # Lists to store loss per epoch for results/visualisations
    train_losses = []
    val_losses = []

    for epoch in range(num_epochs):
        model.train()               # Set the model to training mode
        running_loss = 0.0          # Accumulate losses from each batch
        
        # Training loop
        for inputs, labels in train_loader:
            inputs, labels = inputs.to(device), labels.to(device)
            optimizer.zero_grad()
            outputs = model(inputs)              # Generate predictions (forward pass)
            loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
            loss.backward()                      # Backpropagate the errors to compute gradients
            optimizer.step()
            running_loss += loss.item()
            
        # Calculate average training loss for the epoch
        avg_train_loss = running_loss / len(train_loader)
        train_losses.append(avg_train_loss)
        
        # Validation loop
        model.eval()
        val_loss = 0.0
        with torch.no_grad():
            for inputs, labels in val_loader:
                inputs, labels = inputs.to(device), labels.to(device)
                outputs = model(inputs)
                loss = criterion(outputs, labels)    # Compute validation loss
                val_loss += loss.item()

        # Calculate average validation loss for the epoch 
        avg_val_loss = val_loss / len(val_loader)
        val_losses.append(avg_val_loss)
        
        print(f"Epoch [{epoch+1}/{num_epochs}], Train Loss: {avg_train_loss:.4f}, Val Loss: {avg_val_loss:.4f}")
        
    # Return lists with the losses per epoch for training and validation
    return train_losses, val_losses

# Call the train_model function to handle the training and validation loops
train_losses, val_losses = train_model(model, train_loader, val_loader, optimizer, num_epochs=10)

4.3 Evaluating the Model on Test Data

After completing the training and validation phases, we assess the model's performance using the test data. This step is necessary because it simulates how the model will perform in real-world scenarios, where it needs to identify plant diseases from new images it hasn't previously encountered.

Understanding Test Accuracy in the Context of Plant Disease Detection: Test accuracy measures the proportion of test images for which the model correctly identifies the disease. For example, if the test accuracy is 90%, it means that for 90% of the test images, the model accurately predicted the disease class out of the possible categories (e.g., healthy, infected with disease X, infected with disease Y, etc.).

A high test accuracy indicates that our model is effective at distinguishing between different types of plant diseases and identifying healthy plants. This is particularly important in agricultural settings where accurate and early detection of plant diseases can lead to timely treatment, preventing spread and reducing losses. On the other hand, if the accuracy is lower than expected, it might suggest issues such as overfitting on the training data, underfitting due to a model that's too simple, or insufficient training data for some of the disease classes.

In[10]:
# Evaluate the model on the test set
model.eval()

# Initialise test loss and accuracy tracking variables
test_loss = 0.0
correct = 0
total = 0

# No gradient updates needed for evaluation, which saves memory and computations
with torch.no_grad():
    for inputs, labels in test_loader:
        inputs, labels = inputs.to(device), labels.to(device)

        # Forward pass to get outputs
        outputs = model(inputs)

        # Calculate the batch loss
        loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
        test_loss += loss.item()
        
        # Determine predictions and update correct count
        _, predicted = torch.max(outputs, 1)
        total += labels.size(0)
        correct += (predicted == labels).sum().item()

avg_test_loss = test_loss / len(test_loader)
test_accuracy = correct / total * 100

print(f"Test Loss: {avg_test_loss:.4f}")
print(f"Test Accuracy: {test_accuracy:.2f}%")

Test Loss: 0.5550

# Function for visual insight into model predictions
def display_test_images(data_loader, model, device, classes, num_images=4):
    model.eval()
    images_so_far = 0
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))

    with torch.no_grad():         # Temporarily set all the required gradients to zero
        for i, (inputs, labels) in enumerate(data_loader):
            inputs = inputs.to(device)
            labels = labels.to(device)
            outputs = model(inputs) # Forward pass
            _, predictions = torch.max(outputs, 1)

            for j in range(inputs.size()[0]): # Iterate over all images in the batch
                images_so_far += 1
                ax = plt.subplot(num_images//2, 2, images_so_far)
                ax.axis('off')
                ax.set_title(f'Predicted: {classes[predictions[j]]}\nActual: {classes[labels[j]]}')
                img = inputs.cpu().data[j].numpy().transpose((1, 2, 0))
                mean = np.array([0.485, 0.456, 0.406])     # Normalising mean used during preprocessing
                std = np.array([0.229, 0.224, 0.225])      # Normalising std used during preprocessing
                img = std * img + mean                     # Unnormalise the image
                img = np.clip(img, 0, 1)                   # Clip values to make sure they are between 0 and 1
                plt.imshow(img)

                if images_so_far == num_images:
                    plt.show()
                    return

# Call the function to display test images
display_test_images(test_loader, model, device, color_dataset.classes, num_images=4)

5. Hyperparameter Analysis and Results Visualisation

In this chapter, our goal is to experiment with different hyperparameter configurations to find the optimal settings that enhance our model's performance. We aim to adjust and evaluate the following hyperparameters:

  • Learning Rate: We compare the effects of learning rates of 0.01, 0.001, and 0.0001 to identify which setting provides better convergence without sacrificing the stability of the training process.
  • Dropout Rate: We compare dropout rates of 0.1, 0.25, and 0.5 to determine their impact on the model's ability to generalise and prevent overfitting.
  • Batch Size: We compare batch sizes of 16, 32, and 64 to see how they affect model training dynamics.

To effectively measure and visualize the impact of these hyperparameter adjustments, we use a combination of graphs and tables:

  • Graphical Visualisation: We plot training and validation loss curves for each hyperparameter setting, allowing us to visually assess the effects of changes in real-time.
  • Table Summary: We provide tables summarising key performance metrics such as minimum, maximum, and final epoch losses for training and validation phases. This improves our ability to quickly compare results across different settings.

5.1 Experiment 1: Learning Rate Analysis

Learning rates are pivotal in determining how significantly the model's weights are updated at the end of each training batch, directly influencing the convergence speed and stability. We explore three distinct learning rates:

  • 0.0001: A lower rate to investigate if it prevents overshooting while trading off with slower convergence.
  • 0.001: A more balanced approach.
  • 0.01: A higher rate tested to see if it can achieve faster convergence without destabilising the training process.
In[13]:
# Function to plot the effects of hyperparameters on training and validation loss
def plot_hyperparameter_effects(hyperparams, results, title, param_name):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    for param, (train_losses, val_losses) in results.items():
        epochs = range(1, len(train_losses) + 1)
        plt.plot(epochs, train_losses, label=f'Train Loss - {param_name} {param}')
        plt.plot(epochs, val_losses, label=f'Val Loss - {param_name} {param}')
    
    plt.title(f'Effect of Different {param_name} on {title}')
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()

# Function to create a results table for any hyperparameter
def create_hyperparameter_table(results, param_name):
    headers = f"{param_name} | Min Train Loss | Min Val Loss | Final Train Loss | Final Val Loss"
    print(headers)
    print("-" * len(headers))

    for param, (train_losses, val_losses) in results.items():
        min_train_loss = min(train_losses)
        min_val_loss = min(val_losses)
        final_train_loss = train_losses[-1]
        final_val_loss = val_losses[-1]
        print(f"{param:12} | {min_train_loss:14.4f} | {min_val_loss:12.4f} | {final_train_loss:16.4f} | {final_val_loss:14.4f}")

5.3 Experiment 3: Batch Size Analysis

Batch size affects the model's training dynamics by influencing the accuracy of the gradient estimation and memory usage. We test three batch sizes to observe their impact on training:

  • 16: A smaller batch size which may provide a more robust gradient estimate at the cost of increased noise.
  • 32: A medium batch size that is a good compromise between learning stability and computational efficiency.
  • 64: A larger batch size tested to see if it accelerates training convergence without sacrificing too much model accuracy.

5.4 Summary of Optimal Hyperparameter Findings

Analysis of Hyperparameter Tuning

Our testing involved adjusting three key hyperparameters: learning rate, dropout rate, and batch size. The graphs and accompanying data tables reveal how each parameter affects training and validation loss across epochs.

Learning Rate Analysis:

  • 0.01: High loss values (Train: 3.3491, Val: 3.3371), indicating insufficient learning.
  • 0.001: Better, but still suboptimal with minimal improvement over epochs (Train: 1.2028, Val: 0.7226).
  • 0.0001: Best results with both the lowest training and validation loss (Train: 1.0343, Val: 0.5634), suggesting a balanced convergence rate without overshooting or stagnating.

Based on the graphs, a learning rate of 0.0001 offers the best convergence behavior, demonstrating efficient learning dynamics without significant oscillations or plateauing, therefore, it is the optimal choice.

Dropout Rate Analysis:

  • 0.1: Competent performance but higher loss compared to other rates (Train: 0.5265, Val: 0.3908).
  • 0.25: Lowest validation loss observed (Train: 0.4514, Val: 0.2942), indicating successful generalisation.
  • 0.5: Increasing the dropout to 0.5 deteriorated performance (Train: 0.9485, Val: 0.5755), likely because of too much regularisation leading to underfitting.

The dropout rate of 0.25 is chosen as the optimal setting. It effectively prevents overfitting and also allows the network to learn sufficient complex patterns from the training data.

Batch Size Analysis:

  • 16: Lower batch size resulted in higher variability and general inefficiency (Train: 0.8671, Val: 0.5430).
  • 32: Moderate batch size did not yield improvements in validation loss (Train: 1.0407, Val: 0.5651).
  • 64: Showed the best balance with the lowest validation loss (Train: 0.7426, Val: 0.3876), suggesting more stable and effective learning per batch.

A batch size of 64 ensures that each training epoch is not only computationally efficient but also effective in minimising loss, therefore, it is the optimal choice.

Conclusion

The optimal settings for our Plant Disease CNN model are:

  • Learning Rate: 0.0001
  • Batch Size: 64
  • Dropout Rate: 0.25

These parameters collectively enhance the models learning efficacy and robustness in handling the complex variability within plant disease classification. By employing these settings, we lay a strong foundation for the model, optimising it for both accuracy and generalisation - useful for real-world application.

6. Comparison of Similar Tutorials

In this tutorial, we reference multiple online resources, but in this chapter we focus on comparing our approach to two similar tutorials: the Cassava Leaf Disease Detection tutorial, which uses PyTorch for image classification, and the Plant Disease Detection Using Mask R-CNN tutorial, which uses a Mask R-CNN model for disease detection.

Cassava Leaf Disease Detection Tutorial

  • Objective: Detect diseases in cassava crops to help prevent spread by enabling quick decisions due to quick detection.
  • Model: Uses a pretrained ResNet-152 network, achieving 87% accuracy.
  • Focus: Designed specifically to the Cassava Leaf Disease dataset available on Kaggle.
  • Pros:
    • High accuracy at 87% with an advanced transfer learning model.
    • Good exploratory data analysis and visualisation.
  • Cons:
    • Limited to one dataset, reducing generalisation.
    • Demands higher computational resources than our Custom CNN Tutorial.

Plant Disease Detection Using Mask R-CNN Tutorial

  • Objective: Detect and localise disease symptoms on plant leaves.
  • Model: Uses a pretrained Mask R-CNN (with a ResNet backbone) to provide both classification and segmentation.
  • Focus: Can be applied to a variety of plant types and diseases with spatial localisation.
  • Pros:
    • Offers precise localisation through segmentation masks.
    • Useful for detailed diagnostic research.
  • Cons:
    • More complex setup and therefore slower inference than our Custom CNN Tutorial.
    • Requires greater computational power. Due to this, it's not as beginner friendly as the other two approaches.

Our Custom CNN Tutorial

  • Objective:
    Develop a flexible, custom-designed CNN that can detect various plant diseases across multiple datasets with a focus on real-time applicability in field conditions.

  • Model Architecture:

    • A simple but effective CNN architecture built using PyTorch.
    • Uses two convolutional blocks, dropout for regularisation, and fully connected layers to ensure adaptability and ease of tuning.

  • Dataset and Scope:

    • Uses the PlantVillage dataset, which includes 38 classes of both healthy and diseased leaves, but the model is not limited to this one dataset.
    • The diverse dataset ensures the model learns varied visual features, making it adaptable to other plant disease datasets with minor modifications.

  • Performance and Metrics:

    • Achieves competitive performance (e.g., ~84% test accuracy) while maintaining lower computational overhead compared to the other more complex models.
    • Benefits from hyperparameter analysis, with optimal settings such as a Learning Rate of 0.0001, Batch Size of 64, and Dropout of 0.25 to balance training efficiency and generalisation.

  • Computational Needs and Accessibility:

    • Designed to be lightweight and adaptable.
    • Lower hardware requirements make it more accessible for users in resource-constrained environments or those new to deep learning.

  • Pros:

    • Flexibility: Easily modifiable architecture suited for various plant disease datasets.
    • Accessibility: Lower computational demands allow broader adoption, including in-field deployments.
    • Transparency: Clear hyperparameter tuning and performance evaluation make the model understandable and reproducible.

  • Cons:

    • Initial Accuracy Variability: Without careful fine-tuning, initial model performance can perform worse than the other two tutorial approaches.
    • Additional Setup: Requires users to experiment with hyperparameters and possibly integrate further optimisations for specific datasets.

Key Differences

  • Architecture:
    • The Cassava tutorial uses a deep ResNet-152 for classification,
    • The Mask R-CNN tutorial adds segmentation for localisation, and
    • Our tutorial uses a simpler, customisable CNN.
  • Dataset Flexibility:
    • The Cassava tutorial is dataset-specific, while both our approach and the Mask R-CNN tutorial are designed to work across various plant disease datasets. This shows ours has real-world-applications as a focus due to its wide accessibility goals.
  • Computational Needs:
    • The ResNet-152 and Mask R-CNN approaches are more resource-intensive compared to the moderate requirements of our custom CNN. This shows our pipeline is more focused for beginners.
